hose materiality blends into the immaterial, and on the materials of spaces. Contributors highlight some of the most exciting new developments in the field, such as the emergence of “new materialism,” affect theory, globalization studies, and environmental criticism. Although the book has a Canadian centre, the majority of its contributors consider objects that cross borders or otherwise resist national affiliation. This collection will be valuable to readers within and outside of Canada who are interested in material culture studies and, in addition, will appeal to anyone interested in the central debates taking place in Canadian political and cultural life today, such as climate change, citizenship, shifts in urban and small-town life, and the persistence of imperialism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMaterial culturezCanada. 4aCultural Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Thomas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAlston-O’Connor, Jessa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerland, Jody, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirkwood, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlair, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlair, Jennifer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBoyd, Shelley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalder, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChew, May, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDerksen, Jeff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEpp, Michael, econtributo